{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3992acfb-6f34-4043-9252-d785ba5d3a75","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Getting the file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: Use `dotnet-counters` first\nFor a quick, non-invasive look before committing to a full trace:\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to no SDK in the container, you can download the standalone `dotnet-trace` global tool from the [.NET diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics) and copy it in with `kubectl cp`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b0ad62ec-91bf-49ab-91e1-e37dc4f1ebc8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I can answer directly without tools.","outputTokens":411,"requestId":"9818:2D1D23:ABF051:C95A17:69F400E4"},"id":"8772962e-a7a1-44f3-804d-e78444750bda","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:25:01.317Z","parentId":"ca1507cc-37e1-4108-829c-a1427207d1b2"}
